main event: Two to three circular objects, described as resembling half dollars, dimes, and nickels, were observed over Olean, New York on April 16, 1960.
interesting points: The objects were dull gray in color and appeared to be a large mass until seen through binoculars.
The objects were traveling at an extremely high rate of speed, estimated to be between 10,000 and 15,000 feet in the air.
The objects were observed moving in a close formation, all maintaining the same high rate of speed in a northwesterly direction.
The sighting lasted for a maximum of 15 seconds.
The observers included a civil defense director and a news director, who were both considered reliable witnesses.
sighted object: two to three circular, dull gray objects
